column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRANSPORT DRIVER TRAVELLING WEST ON NORTH ACCESS ROAD, I-30, BENTON, ARKANSAS APPROACHED INTERSECTION TO HIGHWAY 5. NORTH ACCESS ROAD IS FLAT, BUT FROM ITS INTERSECTION WITH HIGHWAY 5, HIGHWAY 5 IS UPHILL. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO NEGOTIATE RIGHT TURN ONTO UPHILL HIGHWAY 5 AND LOST CONTROL. TRANSPORT TANKER AND TRUCK OVERTURNED ON LEFT SIDE. WITNESS ESTIMATED SPEED IMMEDIATELY PRIOR TO OVERTURNING AT ABOUT 10 TO 15 MILES PER HOUR. DRIZZLE AND WET PAVEMENT WERE CONTRIBUTORY FACTORS TO ACCIDENT. ACCIDENT DEEMED PREVENTABLE AND RESULTANT FROM DRIVER ERROR. ACTION TAKEN AT TIME DISCOVERED: POLICE, AMBULANCE, FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ALL AT THE SCENE WITHIN 5 TO 10 MINUTES OF ACCIDENT. ARKANSAS POLLUTION CONTROL AND ECOLOGY CONTACTED WITHIN MINUTES OF THE ACCIDENT AND RESPONDED. DRIVER REMOVED TO HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE. FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHING AREA. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES CONTACTED TO CONTAIN FLOW OF WATER/GASOLINE FLOWING INTO GRASSY MEDIAN BETWEEN NORTH ACCESS ROAD AND WESTBOUND LANES OF I-30. TRANSPORT TRUCK AND TANKER RIGHTED BY USE OF AIRBAGS. TRAFFIC PERIMETER ESTABLISHED PRIOR TO COMMENCEMENT OF OPERATIONS. CLEAN UP OPERATIONS COMMENCED. APPROXIMATELY 6 INCHES OF DIRT HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM THE MEDIAN FOR A DISTANCE OF APPROXIMATELY 30 X 100 FEET. NOW AWAITING FINAL SOIL TESTS. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: RENEWED EMPHASIS ON DRIVERS' UPGRADE TRAINING AND EDUCATION BY MEANS OF VIDEOS, TESTING AND PERSONAL OBSERVATION, PARTICULARLY DANGERS WHILE OPERATING DURING WET PAVEMENT CONDITIONS.

THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE DOME LID GASKET AND LEAKED ONLY WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED.  THEREFORE, THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE SPILLAGE.  THE SPILLAGE FROM THE DEFECTIVE DOME LID GASKET WAS CONFINED TO THE TOP AREA OF  THE TANK CAR SHELL.  NO MATERIAL RELEASED MADE CONTACT WITH THE GROUND.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, MAKING NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE DEFECTIVE DOME LID GASKET.  AFTER REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AND THE TANK CAR SHELL WAS DECONTAMINATED, THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

METROPOLITIAN ARRIVED ON SITE AT 8:00 AM. ROBERT WHITNEY WAS THE REPRESENTATIVE FRIM METRO.  FIRST MR. WHITNEY DROPPED AND LINED THE REPLACEMENT ROLL-OFF BOX.  NEXT HE BEGAN TO REMOVE THE FULL ROLL-OFF BOX FROM THE STORAGE BAY.  HE HAD TO REPOSITION THE ROLL OFF BOX IN THE BAY TO REMOVE IT.  THE ROLL OFF BOX WAS PULLED OUT 3/4 OF THE WAY FROM THE STORAGE BAY THEN HE BEGAN TO LIFT THE BOX TO PLACE IT ON THE TRUCK.  THE BOX WAS RAISED TO A 45 DEGREE ANGLE, WHICH CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF LIQUID, AND 1 CUBIC YARD OF SLUDGE TO SPILL FROM THE ROLL-OFF BOX.  THE 150 GALLONS OF LIQUID ENTERED THE STORM SEWER.  THE SEWER WAS THEN CONTAINED TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LIQUIDS FROM ENTERING THE STORM SEWER, AND THE SLUDGE WAS CLEANED UP BY PERSONNEL FROM SIEMENTS AND PLACED INTO THE REPLACEMENT ROLL-OFF BOX.  AROUND 10:45 AM, THE ROLL-OFF LEFT THE FACILITY TRANSPORTED BY METRO.

column168: OUR TRAILER (7000 WG MC-307) WAS TRANSPORTING A BULK SHIPMENT OF AQUA AMMONIA (AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE 29.4%) FROM NATALBANY, LA TO MOBILE, AL. IT WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON MISSISSIPPI I-10 WHEN THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. THE LEAK WAS ACTUALLY OBSERVED BY ANOTHER TRUCKER WHO NOTIFIED OUR DRIVER. THE DRIVER PULLED OVER ON I-10 AT EXIT 61 IN GAUTIER, MS. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE HOME OFFICE AND ALSO CONTACTED 911. THE TRAILER HAD DEVELOPED A CRACK IN A SEAM (ABOUT THE SIZE OF A PENCIL) AND WAS LEAKING AQUA AMMONIA. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO USE A SCREWDRIVER AND WRENCH TO TAP THE LEAK POINT WHICH SLOWED THE AMOUNT LEAKING OUT DOWN TO A DRIP. PROPER NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE AND WE DISPATCHED AN EMPTY TRAILER AND PORTABLE PUMP TO THE LOCATION IN ORDER TO TRANSFER THE LOAD FROM THE LEAKING TRAILER TO A GOOD ONE. MISSISSIPPI DEQ SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE AND OUR COMPANY CONTRACTED WITH CET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (MOBILE, AL) TO OVERSEE AND FACILITATE ANY CLEAN UP. APPROXIMATELY ONE YARD OF SAND WAS USED TO DIKE THE LEAK AREA AND ABSORB THE MATERIAL THAT WAS SPILLED. BASED ON THE LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL SPILLED, NO NEUTRALIZATION OR REMEDIATION WAS REQUIRED. THE TRAILER WHICH CRACKED HAS BEEN SENT TO A REPAIR SHOP. TWO LOAD OF PRODUCT WAS ORDERED 1 DIESEL FUEL AND 1 II 2 FUEL OIL. PREMIUM HAD THE HIGH SULPHUR FUEL OIL AND ALSO ADVANTAGE HAD LOADED HIGH SULPHUR FUEL ADVANTAGE WAS THE FIRST TO DELIVER THEIR LOAD OF HIGH SULPHUR. THEN PREMIUM BROUGHT THEIR LOAD OF HIGH SULPHUR IN. PREMIUM NOT KNOWING THAT ADVANTAGE BROUGHT IN HE SAME FUEL, STARTED TO UNLOAD HIS H/S FUEL THE TANK FILLED AND A SPILL TOOK PLACE. WE SPILLED ABOUT 200-300 OF H/S FUEL. EPA WAS CALLED, PRO-TERRA THE CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS CALLED. MOUNT VERNON FIRE DEPARTMENT HELPED CLEAN UP STAND LIQUID FUEL OFF GROUND AND LEFT. EPA WESS DRAKE WAS ON THE SCENE AND MONATOUY THE CLEAN UP. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS HAULED TO COLUMBUS OHIO ENVIROTECH TO BE DISPOSED OF. IN THE FUTURE ALL LOAD GOING INTO MICKEY OIL WILL HAVE TO BE HAVE STICK READ TO SEE WHAT THE TANK HAS IN THEM INSTEAD OF A PAPER NOTE LEFT BY THE OWNER SAYING TANK HAS 50 INCH GO AHEAD AND PUMP LOAD IN. THE DRIVER IS THE ALTMATE CHECK WHEN DELIVERING THE PRODUCT.

column168: DRIVER WAS DIRECTED TO CONNECT TO A SPECIFIC LINE.  THE RECEIVER PERSON CHECKED THE PIPING AND NOTED THAT THE TANK THAT THE PIPING ENTERED WAS THE CORRECT TANK.  THE RECEIVER THEN RECEIVED A RADIO CALL AND LEFT THE AR EA.  DRIVER STARTED THE UNLOAD PRECESS AND WALKED OVER TO THE TANK INDICATED.  THERE WERE UNUSUAL SOUNDS INSIDE THE TANK.  DRIVER HEADED FOR TRUCK TO CLOSE VALVES AND ON THE WAY WAS AFFECTED BY CHLORINE GAS FUMES THAT WERE COMING FROM THE REACTION IN THE STORAGE TANK.  HE CONTINUED AND CLOSED THE TRUCK VALVES. THE SUN COMPANY LOADER RETURNED AND ALSO WAS AFFECTED BY THE FUMES.  BOTH DRIVER AND SUN CO EMPLOYEE WERE TAKEN TO CHESTER CROZER MEDICAL CENTER FOR CHECKUP, DUE TO THEIR COUGHING FROM FUMES. BOTH WERE EXAMINED AND RELEASED.  SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION SHOWED THE DELIVERED PRODUCT & PRODUCT IN STORAGE TANK WERE INCOMPATIBLE.

THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

A CONTRACTOR WAS AT CSXT RAIL YARD IN WAYCROSS CA    TO REDUCE AN TANK CAR.  AEX 26008. CONTRACTOR HAD HAULED UP TO TRAILER TRUCK (2556) AND STARTED PUMP. THE TRAILER HOSE CAME LOOSE FROM THE TRUCK AND RELEASED ABOUT 20 GAL. OF PRODUCT BEFORE PUMPING COULD BE SHUT DOWN.  THE CONTRACTOR VACUUMED UP AS MUCH FREE PRODUCT AS WE COULD AND PUT DOWN ABSORBANT PADS.  CSXT RESPONDED A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR TO EVACUATE IMPACTED SOILS.  FOUND SOME PRODUCT GOT INTO STORM DRAIN  AND FLOWED INTO A DITCH.   DITCH WAS FILLED, PUMPED UP ABOUT 3000 GAL OF WATER AND EVACUATED 6 TO 7 YARDS OF SOIL. MATERIALS STOCK PILED ON SITE PENDING TRANSPORT FOR DISPOSAL.

THE RELEASED MATERIAL SPILLED ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR REPAIRING THE DEFECTIVE DOME LID GASKET.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS NOR OTHER INDICATORS THAT WOULD HAVE ALLOWED US TO READILY IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS AS BEING REGULATED.  THE FREIGHT HAS RELEASED FOR PICK UP BY THE SHIPPER.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: ON DEC 15, 1997, A TRUCK TRANSPORTATION SEVEN WHITE METAL BOXES WHICH CONTAINED DEPLETED AND SLIGHTLY ENRICHED URANIUM RESIDUES FROM THE FERNALD ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT PROJECT WAS EN ROUTE TO MERCURY, NEVADA, WHEN THE TRUCK DRIVER NOTICED CLEAR LIQUID LEAKING SLOWLY FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRUCK LEFT FERNALD ON DEC. 12, 1997. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE FERNALD EMERGENCY DUTY OFFICER AND THE DECISION TREE WAS MADE TO MOVE THE TRUCK OFF THE ROAD AND PARK IT AT A TRUCK STOP IN KINGMAN, ARIZONA.  THE FERNALD EMERGENCY OPERATION CENTER WAS ACTIVATED TO SUPPORT THE DRIVER AT THE SCENE AND NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO DOE IN OHIO AND WASHINGTON, LOCAL AND FEDERAL EPAS, LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND KEY STAKEHOLDERS.  A RADIOLOGICAL ASSISTANCE PROGRAM TEAM FROM DOE-ALBUQUERQUE (THE CLOSEST RADIOLOGICAL JURISDICTION TO THE INCIDENT SITE) MONITORED THE TRUCK TO DETERMINE IF THE FLUID WAS RADIOACTIVE. AFTER MONITORING NO CONTAMINATION, THE RAP TEAM ACCESSED THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRUCK. INITIAL SURVEYS OF THE TRUCK'S INTERIOR SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF CONTAMINATION OR RADIOLOGICAL HAZARD.  THERE APPEARED TO BE A BREACH IN ONE OF THE WHITE METAL BOXES FROM WHICH FLUID WAS LEAKING.  A DOE FERNALD TEAM DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS THE RESULT OF A CRACK IN THE BASE OF THE WHITE METAL BOX NEAREST TO THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE FERNALD TEAM REPAIRED THE BOX IN PLACE ON THE TRAILER.

WHILE DEPARTING FROM THE KANSAS CITY ARGENTINE YARD, TRAIN M-GALTEAI-20, DERAILED NINE CARS ACCOUNT PASSING OVER A TRANSVERSE FISSURE RAIL DEFECT IN THE TRACK STRUCTURE. TRAIN SPEED WAS 20 MPH. LOADED TANK CAR GATX 38583 WAS ONE OF THE DERAILED CARS. UPON STRIKING A BRIDGE PIER FOR THE 42ND ST. OVERPASS, A VERTICAL SPLIT OCCURRED IN THE TANK CAR TANK NERAR THE WELD FOR THE TANK HEAD. FIRE ERUPTED AND CONSUMED NEARLY ALL OF THE PROPYLENE IN THE CAR. THE FIRE WAS PERMITTED TO BURN ITSELF OUT (ABOUT FOUR HOURS LATER). THE BRIDGE SPAN WAS DESTROYED ($ IN ITEM 23C). AN EVACUATION OF APPROXIMATELY 1600 PEOPLE FROM ADJACENT RESIDENCES AND BUSINESSES RESULTED. PLEASE REFER TO BNSF 6180.54, REPORT NUMBER KS-1297-102.

ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBENT. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT BACK. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DMP.

DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE EMITTING A STRONG ETHER BASED ODOR. FEDEX DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST JARED MCADAMS OPENED THE PACKING LIST TO FIND WHAT APPEARED TO BE DESCRIBE AS ETHER. THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT. I NOTIFIED THE ATLANTA CASFO AND SPOKE TO SPECIAL AGENT CHARLES PHILLIPS. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS LABELING SHIPPING PAPERS NOR OTHER INDICATORS THAT WOULD HAVE ALLOWED US TO READILY IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS AS REGULATED.

THE THREE PIECES BEING HELD WERE PART OF A MULTI PIECE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT THAT ORIGINATED OUT OF VERO BEACH FLORIDA ON FLIGHT #7346. THESE PIECES WERE TRANSLOADED ONTO FLIGHT 1916 ON 12/8 AND TRANSITED FROM ORLANDO TO NEWARK. THE FIRST PIECE IN THE SHIPMENT TRAVELING ON AIRBILL # 800 929800 100, SPILLED UPON ARRIVAL INTO MCO-R AND WAS CONTAINED. THE ENCLOSED MSDS WITH THE SHIPMENT SHOWED THAT THE MATERIAL SHOULD HAVE BEEN DECLARED AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. CONSEQUENTLY, THIS ALERTED US TO THE FACT THAT THERE WERE OTHER PACKAGES FROM THE SAME SHIPPER (OCEAN SPRAY) THAT WERE POSSIBLY THE SAME MATERIAL (GRAPEFRUIT OIL). THE PACKAGES TRAVELING ON THE FOLLOWING AIRBILLS, 8009-2980-0122, 8009-2980-0085, 8009-2980-0096 WERE LOCATED UPON ARRIVAL OF THE FLIGHT FROM MCO-R AND HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

THE FEDEX DELIVERY DRIVER, KEVIN CARNEY COMPLETED THE DELIVERY OF A RADIOACTIVE YELLOW III TO THE IDAHO NATIONAL ENGINEERING AND ENVIRONMENTAL LABORATORIES AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM. THE SHIPMENT WAS SURVEYED AT ITS DELIVERY POINT AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE SOURCE RODS, EU-152 WAS MISSING FROM THE LEAD PIG. THE FEDEX DELIVERY DRIVER, KEVIN CARNEY AND HIS VEHICLE WERE LOCATED AT 1730 (MST) IN IDAHO FALLS MAKING A PICKUP AT ANOTHER INEEL FACILITY. A SURVEY PERFORMED BY INEEL PERSONNEL VERIFIED THAT THE SOURCE ROD WAS IN THE BACK OF THE VEHICLE ON ONE OF THE SHELVES. THE SOURCE ROD HAD NOT BEEN BREACHED AND THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION FOUND IN THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER AND THE VEHICLE WERE RELEASED BY INEEL AT APPROXIMATELY 18:19 (MST). APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS TO THE AFFECTED REGULATORY AGENCIES HAVE BEEN MADE. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER REPORT # IS 45429.

column168: ON DECEMBER 2, 1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 AM, A TANKER TRUCK OWNED BY DSI TRANSPORT, INC. CARRYING ETHYLENE CHLORIDE FROM FORMOSA PLASTIC OVERTURNED ON INTERSTATE 110 SOUTH NEAR THE 22ND STREET OVERPASS.  AT 8:45AM ON DECEMBER 2, 1997, LYNN BRAUD OF DSI TRANSPORT PROVIDED VERBAL NOTIFICATIONS OF THIS INCIDENT TO MS. AMY ABADIE OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE (INCIDENTS #975208).  DSI REPRESENTATIVES, ALONG WITH PERSONNEL FROM THE BATON ROUGE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  A PORTION OF THE ETHYLENE CHLORIDE FROM THE TANKER TRUCK REACHED A NEARBY STORM DRAIN, LEADING TO A DITCH AND A CANAL, DEQ INSTALLED A DAM IN THE CANAL TO PREVENT ANY MIGRATION OF THE WATER WHICH MAY HAVE CONTAINED ETHYLENE CHLORIDE.  DSI IMMEDIATELY ENGAGED LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL, WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF ALL AFFECTED WATER.  DSI IS PRESENTLY COORDINATING WITH DEQ AND CONDUCTING FURTHER SAMPLING OF THE CANAL AND NEARBY.

column168: ON 120497 AT APPROXIMATELY 7PM, MANAGER SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A REPORT OF A CONTAINER THAT WAS EMITTING A FOUL ODOR AT THE ENGLEWOOD PIGGYBACK RAMP. THE INITIAL REPORT STATED THERE WAS NO LIQUID VISIBLE. REEDER CONTACTED THE REPORTING PERSON, CHIEF CLERK, MICHAEL TAYLOR. TAYLOR STATED THE CONTAINER WAS STINKING WHEN HE CAME IN AT 2PM. HE THOUGHT IT WAS JUST A VAPOR RELEASE AND IT WOULD GET BETTER. AT 7PM THE TANK WAS STINKING SO HE HAD IT MOVED TO A REMOTE LOCATION AT THE WEST END OF THE RAMP. UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER OBSERVED THREE STREAMS OF LIQUID ABOUT THE SIZE OF A PENCIL COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER. SINCE THE CONTAINER WAS INSULATED AND JACKETED IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINE THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK. REEDER CONTACTED THE CONTAINER OWNER, STOLT TANK CONTAINERS, INC. THEY AGREED TO SEND ANOTHER TANK AND PAY FOR AN EMERGENCY TRANSFER. THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED ON 12/5/97 AND BOTH CONTAINERS WERE RELEASED. THE CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED INTO UTCU 461206.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY JESSE CONTRERAS, MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, WHO REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING LPG. THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN BOWL RACK #240. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD AND MET WITH TOM BEESE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER AND PROCEEDED TO INSPECT THE LEAKING TANK CAR. A THREE FOOT WIDE ICE TRAIL WAS OBSERVED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, DOWN THE LFET SIDE WITH FREE LIQUID FLOWING ONTO THE GROUND. A 3 SQUARE FOOT GROUND AREA WAS ICED UP FROM THE LIQUID POOLING IN THE BALLAST. UON APPROACHING THE CAR, MONITOR READINGS INDICATED THE VAPOR CONCENTRATIONS EXCEEDED THE 10% LEL. AT THIS POINT, THE SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE BOWL YARD WERE CEASED. RIALTO FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON SITE AND PROVIDED SUPPRESSION PROTECTION. UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER, OBSERVED LIQUID STREAMING FROM THE PORT PLUG ON THE GAUGING DEVICE. THE 1/4 INCH PLUG HAD A WEEP HOLE IN THE CENTER WHICH ALLOWED THE LIQUID TO ESCAPE. THE "T" HANDLE ON THE VALVE WAS MISSING THE FINGER PORTION TO TIGHTEN THE VALVE. THE PACKING GLAND HAD TO BE LOOSENED IN ORDER TO RECESS THE DEVICE ENOUGH TO PULL BACK THE RETAINER TO ACCESS THE VALVE STEM.THE VALVE STEM WAS THEN FINGER TIGHTENED AND FURTHER SECURED UTILIZING PLIERS, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. IT APPEARS THE VALVE STEM HAD ONLY BEEN FINGER TIGHTENED DURING THE LOADING PROCESS AND VIBRATED LOOSE DURING TRANSIT. THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS SECURED AND THE PROTECTIVE COVER REPOSITIONED. THE REMAINING VALVES WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN APPLIED WATER OVER THE TOP OF THE CAR TO DISSIPATE THE ICE AND LINGERING VAPORS. NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED.THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR NOTIFICATION PURPOSED AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY FORCES, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER IN TRAILER STORAGE ROW E05, STALL#225. AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED TOXIC, IT WAS ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MGR COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF RAMP AND OBSERVED A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN ONE GALLON) ON THE PAVEMENT AT THE REAR OF THE CHASSIS. DUE TO THE LOW TEMPERATURES, VERY LITTLE VAPOR ODOR WAS DETECTED. THE GROUND AREA WAS COVERED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO ELIMINATE ANY ODORS. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, OBSERVED METAL 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER. TY-PATCH WAS USED TO SECURE THE LADING AND APPEARED TO BE PROPERLY APPLIED AT THE REAR DOORS, HOWEVER, CLOSER INSPECTION NOTED THE FABRIC MATERIAL WAS LOOSE, ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO MOVE. BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C REQUIRES DOUBLE BAYING OF DRUMS ON EACH LAYER DUE TO THE TESTED STRENGTH OF THE FABRIC IS EXCEEDED WHEN IT IS ONLY APPLIED AT THE REAR OF THE LADING. THIS PARTICULAR LOAD WAS ONLY SECURED AT THE REAR DOORS AND IS NOT AN APPROVED METHOD PER BOE 6C. UPON REMOVING THE TY-PATCH, INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS INDICATED THE LEAKER TO BE NEAR THE REAR OF THE LOAD. THE FIRST ROW OF DRUMS WAS REMOVED AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS LOCATED ON THE RIGHT SIDE. THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY AN ELEVATED FLOOR SCREW HEAD. THE SCREW HEAD WAS ADJACENT TO THE REAR DECK PLATE AND ELEVATED ROUGHLY 1/8 OF AN INCH, AND WHEN THE DRUM WAS POSITIONED FOR LOADING, IT WAS DRUG OVER THE TOP OF THE SCREW HEAD PEELING THE BOTTOM CHIME METAL BACK. IT APPEARS THIS DAMAGE WAS DONE DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING THE SHIPPER'S DISP0SITION. THE CONTAINER WAS DECONED PER THE SHIPPER'S RECOMMENDATIONS, AND THE REMAINING DRUMS RELOADED. AN EMPTY "DUMMY" WAS USED TO FILL THE VOID OF THE SINGLE DAMAGED DRUM, AND THE LADING WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE ONLY TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY FORCES REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO TH ICFT RAMP AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN SECTION  E05, STALL #282.  THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE AND CORROSIVE, WITH THE SHIPPING PAPERS DESCRIBING THE CONTENTS AS AMINES.  THERE WAS A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN 1 GALLON) ON THE PAVEMENT A THE REAR OF THE CHASSIS. THE LIQUID WAS DRIPPING THROUGH THE REAR DOORS OF THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER. ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL AREA AND THE RESIDUE REMOVED.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN "DIAPERED" AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION.  SEAL A-985364 WAS REMOVED AND THE READ DOORS OPENED TO INSPECT THE LADING, WHICH CONSISTED OF DOUBLE STACKED 55 GALLON DRUMS THROUGHOUT THE CONTAINER.  THE BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF VERTICAL AND HORIZONTAL 2X6 BOARDS, WHICH APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE TO RESTRAIN THE LADING, HOWEVER, WAS NOT IN CONFORMANCE WITH THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE PROPER SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR RAILROAD TRANSPORTATION.  IT APPEARED THE DRUMS HAD MOVED DURING TRANSIT AS THERE WAS A 2 INCH GAP BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE REAR SECUREMENT.  UPON REMOVING THE DRUMS, LOCATED A SINGLE DRUM ON THE TOP LAYER, 2 ROWS BACK FROM THE RER DOORS, AND SECOND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDEWALL, THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THE BOTTOM CHIME HAD SUSTAINED DAMAGED FORM PASSING OVER AN UNKNOWN OBJECT, WHICH PEELED A 1/8 INCH PIECE OF THE METAL BACK. ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO WEEP FROM THE DRUM. THIS DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED PRIOR TO LOADING, AS IT WAS ON THE TOP LAYER AND SITTING ON PLYWOOD USE TO SEPARATE THE TWO LAYERS OF DRUMS.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A OVERPACK TO SECURE IT.  AN ADDITIONAL EIGHT DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE SUFFICIENTLY DAMAGED FROM THE LOAD SHIFTING THAT THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  ALL WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACKS TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER DAMAGE AND POTENTIAL RELEASE.  THE CONTAINER WAS DECONTAMINATED PER THE MANUFACTURERS RECOMMENDED PROTOCOLS AND SECURED.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE RELOADED INTO A HIGHWAY TRAILER FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER PER THE MANUFACTURERS INSTRUCTIONS.  NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED. DUE TO THE TYPE OF MATERIAL AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE ICTF SECURITY FORCES, ADVISING THEY HAD OBSERVED A LEAKING CONTAINER ON INBOUND TRAIN. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF RAMP AND NOTED THE ABOVE 2O FOOT CONTAINER IN THE WELL OF DTTX 25373 (DOUBLE STACK) ON YARD  TRACK #805, WHICH PRODUCT POOLED IN THE WELL OF THE CAR.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CONTAINER REMOVED FROM THE CAR AND PLACED ONTO A CHASSIS, WHERE IT WAS "DIAPERED" FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED.  THE WELL OF THE RAIL CAR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE PAINT AND RELEASED FOR RELOADING.  UPON REMOVING SEAL WOS 557S, THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED TO REVEAL EXTREMELY STRONG ODORS BEING EMITTED FROM WITHIN. BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS NONEXISTENT EXCEPT FOR A SINGLE 2X4 ACROSS THE REAR DOORWAY. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED SECUREMENT PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON THE RAILROAD.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF 5 GALLON PAILS, 30 GALLON OPEN HEAD DRUMS, AND 55 GALLON CLOSED HEAD DRUMS, ALL OF WHICH WERE INTERMINGLED THROUGHOUT THE LOAD. VIRTUALLY ALL OF THE DRUMS IN THIS LOAD HAD EXTENSIVE DAMAGE FROM SPINNING IN PLACE AND ABRADING AGAINST ADJACENT DRUMS DURING TRANSIT.  4 ROWS FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, A 55 GALLON DRUM BELOW THE UPPER ROLLING PALLET AND TOPPLED ON TO A 30 GALLON DRUM, CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE SIDEWALL OF THE 55 GALLON DRUM BELOW HAD SHIFTED OFF OF A HOOP.  APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THIS DRUM AS A RESULT.  AN ADDITIONAL, FOUR OF THE FIVE GALLON PAILS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD HAD THE C CARRY HANDLED IMBEDDED INTO THE SIDES CAUSING THE PAILS TO FAIL AND LEAK.  IT IS ESTIMATED THEY LOST APPROXIMATELY ON GALLON EACH.  THERE WERE ALL PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM FOR SECUREMENT AND CONTAINMENT.  AS THE ENTIRE FLOOR WAS COVERED WITH PRODUCT, AN EMPTY CONTAINER NYKU 232937, WAS BROUGHT IN, AND THE LADING TRANSFERRED. THE RESIDUE WAS CLEANED TO THE BEST POSSIBLE, HOWEVER, CENTENNIAL WAS ADVISED TO HAVE NYK INSPECT THE FLOOR FOR POSSIBLE REMOVAL DUE TO THE GROSS CONTAMINATION.  DUE TO THE TYPE OF COMMODITY AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE ICTF SECURITY FORCES, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER IN THE CHASSIS STORAGE LOT.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE CONTAINER ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF RAMP, LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN SPACE #89, AND OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID (LESS THAN ONE GALLON) POOLED ON THE PAVEMENT TO THE REAR OF THE CHASSIS. THE LEAKING PRODUCT APPEARED TO HAVE SUBSIDED.  THE GROUND SPILL AREA WAS COVERED WITH ABSORBENT AND THE RESIDUE REMOVED.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION.  THE SECURITY SEAL, PETROLITE 5069, WAS REMOVED AND THE REAR DOORS OPENED TO INSPECT THE LADING.  THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER HAD 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT.  THE DRUMS WERE SECURED WITH STRIPS OF TY-PATCH MATERIAL AND METAL BANDING, BOTH OF WHICH WERE LOOSE.  IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM, THE CONTENTS REQUIRED OFF LOADING.  DURING THE OFF LOADING PROCESS, LOCATED A SINGLE DRUM AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDEWALL, BOTTOM LAYER, 2 ROWS IN FROM THE REAR DOORS, THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE SIDE BELOW THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP.  THE STEEL BANDING USED TO SECURE THE LOAD HAD BEEN FOLDED OVER, CREATING CRIMP IN THE BANDING, WHICH CUT THROUGH THE SIDEWALL OF THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT HAD ALSO BEEN FOLDED OVER, HOWEVER, BECAUSE THE CRIMP WAS AGAINST THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP, THE DRUM DID NOT FAIL.  THE DRUM DID SUSTAIN HEAVY DAMAGE TO THE ROLLING HOOP FROM THE BANDING ABRADING AGAINST IT AND WAS DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT.  AS THE LIQUID FROM THE LEAKING DRUM HAD MOVED FORWARD INTO THE CONTAINER, THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE REMOVED.  THE FLOOR WAS DECONTAMINATED PER THE MANUFACTURERS RECOMMENDATIONS, AND THE LADING REINSTALLED IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE 2 DAMAGED DRUMS ARE BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THE MANUFACTURERS REQUEST. DUE TO THE TYPE OF COMMODITY AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

BACK AT DMP AREA ALL AFFECTED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED TO A PH OF 7 (WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE) AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE SORT AT THIS FEDEX STATION.  PACKAGE WAS AN ENVELOPE CONTAINING 3 PINT PLASTIC BOTTLES.  ONE OF THE BOTTLES HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND HAD LEAKED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  CONTENTS WAS IMPROPERLY PACKAGED AND WAS NOT MARKED AND LABELED AS BEING A DANGEROUS GOODS COMMODITY.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE DAMAGE, AND THEY FAXED AN MSDS TO THE STATION SPILL CLEAN UP SPECIALIST. I CONTACTED DOUG PESCE WITH FAA AND HE WAS TO INVESTIGATE THIS INCIDENT. PACKAGE CONTENTS WERE HELD FOR INVESTIGATION, AND CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED AND IT WAS REQUESTED THAT HE PICKED UP HIS PACKAGE.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Ripped or Torn
column168: THE BOX HAD BEEN INSPECTED AND REFUSED FOR SEVERAL DISCREPANCIES. FEDEX DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST JOSE MERCADO HAD SET THE BOX ON THE FLOOR AND TURNED HIS BACK TO THE PACKAGE WHEN IT EXPLODED.  DEBRIS WAS SCATTERED AND THE BOX WAS SHREDDED.  THERE WAS NO EXPOSURE INCIDENT AS DEFINED BY OSHA.  I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE FAA DUTY OFFICER IN THE EASTERN REGION.  I SPOKE TO FAA SPECIAL AGENT JOHN EPSTEIN.  THE PIECES OF THE FREIGHT WERE RECOVERED AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE AREA THEN WAS BLEACHED TO KILL ANY POSSIBLE CONTAMINATION.  I THEN NOTIFIED THE CDC IN ATLANTA, I SPOKE WITH AND ADVISED DR. MATTHEWS.  I ATTEMPTED SEVERAL TIMES TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER, DR. MATTHEWS.  IT WAS NOT UNTIL 02:00 ON 12/16 THAT I WAS ABLE TO REACH THE SHIPPER.  I ASKED DR WILLIAMSON IF HE OR HIS EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN TRAINED TO SHIP DANGEROUS GOODS PER HM 126G. DR. WILLIAMSON REFUSED TO ANSWER THIS QUESTION AND REQUESTED THAT I CONTACT HIM LATER IN THE DAY ON 12/16. I ATTEMPTED TO DO THAT TWICE BUT EVEN THOUGH I LEFT SEVERAL MESSAGES WITH HIS WIFE, HE NEVER CALLED BACK.  THE FREIGHT WAS BEING HELD PENDING AND INSPECTION BY THE FAA.  FEDEX HAS CHOSEN NOT ACCEPT ANY MORE SHIPMENTS FROM THIS CUSTOMER UNTIL WE RECEIVE REASONABLE AND WRITTEN ASSURANCES THAT THEY MEET THE TRAINING REQUIREMENTS AND THAT A SIMILAR INCIDENT WILL NEVER BE REPEATED.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE OUTER BOX OF THIS SHIPMENT HAD BEEN LEAKING AND SMELLED OF FUEL. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED,  OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL SOME TYPE OF ENGINE PART LEAKING  DIESEL FUEL.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NO WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION AND DISPOSITION.

column42: AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORT WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS BY THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST, THERE WERE A VARIETY OF ITEMS INSIDE THE BOX, MANY WRAPPED IN COPY PAPER AS CUSHIONING MATERIAL. THESE INCLUDED COFFEE, VITAMINS, HERBS, SPICES, POWDERED DRINK MIX, PAPERWORK, A MARBLE EGG, A CONTAINER, A DRINK OF 20 OZ, AND A 2 OZ  AEROSOL HAIR SPRAY. THE 20 OZ DRINK WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WHICH SATURATED THE ENTIRE BOX.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, PACKAGED, OR DOCUMENTED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, YET IT CONTAINED AN AEROSOL CAN.  THUS THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD FOR UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION.  I REPORTED THIS TO FAA AGENT JEANETTE DEAN ON 12/30.  I HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER OF THE PROBLEM WITH THEIR PACKAGE AT THIS TIME.

PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING SORT AT HUB.  SPILLED MATERIAL NEUTRALIZED AND PLACED IN STEEL SALVAGE DRUM WITH REMAINDER OF PACKAGE.  SPILLAGE APPEARS TO BE DUE TO DEFECTIVE CLOSURES, THERE IS NO APPARENT DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE. SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

column25: M S A S CARGO INT'L
column168: THIS WAS A HEAVYWEIGHT SHIPMENT OF A PART SHRINK WRAPPED TO A PALLET.  WHEN THE PALLET WAS MOVED DURING LOADING THE PART LEAKED FUEL OUT ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE.  THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR OF KEROSENE.  THE FEDEX AIRCRAFT MECHANIC WAS ASKED TO LOOK AT THE PACKAGE BY THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST.  THE MECHANIC SAID THE FUEL LINES WERE NOT CAPPED AND RAGS WERE PLACED AROUND THE FUEL LINES AND THUS THIS WAS ALSO IMPROPERLY PACKAGED IN THAT RESPECT ALSO.  ALSO THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT PACKAGED, MARKED, LABELED, OR DOCUMENTED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. I NOTIFIED CHUCK SCHAFFER AT THE FAA ON 12/31.  I SPOKE WITH AN OSCAR PEREZ AT MSAS. HE SAID THAT THEY WERE THE FREIGHT FORWARDERS AND THE SHIPPER IS REALLY LANG CHILE AIRLINES, 2261 NORTHWEST 66TH AVE, BUILDING 702, MIAMI, FLORIDA 33126.  I CONTACTED THEM TO LET THEM KNOW THERE WAS A PROBLEM WITH THE SHIPMENT.  OSCAR PEREZ ALSO MENTIONED THAT THIS SHIPMENT HAD ALREADY COME INBOUND FROM CHILE ALTHOUGH HE DID NOT KNOW WHAT CARRIER IT WAS SHIPPED WITH THEN.  COPY OF AIRBILL ENCLOSED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 PM ON 12-11-97, JOHNNY BAZILE WAS MOVING A CRATE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CONTAINING UN2659 SODIUM CHLORAECETE, 6.1, PG III.  THIS PIECE TIPPED OVER ON ITS EDGE WHEN HE CAME OVER THE TRACKS INTO THE HANGAR. HE TRIED TO PUT THE PIECE DOWN BEFORE IT WENT ALL THE WAY OVER BUT HE COULD NOT MAKE IT IN TIME. WHEN THE PIECE FELL ON ITS SIDE THE TOP CAME OFF AND THE CARGO STARTED TO FALL OUT, SO HE HURRIED AND FLIPPED IT RIGHT SIDE UP BUT BY THAT TIME IT WAS TOO LATE AND THE SIDE BUSTED OUT.  HE WAS NO HIGHER THAN FOUR INCHES OFF THE GROUND WHEN THIS HAPPENED.  NOW AFTER THIS HAPPENED JOHNNY CAME INSIDE AND TOLD M. ASHCROFT AND D. NUEBURGER, WE THEN WENT OUTSIDE TO INSPECT IT AND WE TRIED TO PULL THE CRATE AWAY FROM ONE SIDE SO WE COULD SEE HOW DAMAGED THIS WAS.  WE THEN NOTICED A PILE ON THE GROUND, AND WE CAME INSIDE CHEMTREC AD GERALD AT G.A.C.  GERALD THEN CAME OVER AND INSPECTED THE CRATE THE WE CAME INSIDE AD HE CALLED AVCOM.  AT THIS TIME CHEMTREC FAXED US OVER AN MSDS SHEET ON GRGO. WE THEN TOLD EVERYONE TO EXIT THE HANGAR AND WAIT FOR AVCOM TO SHOW UP.  THEN WE CALLED CHARLIE AT HOME AND ROGER MASCARO AT HOME AND THEY BOT CAME OUT.  THAT WAS ABOUT 1:00 A.M. THE REASON IT WAS A LITTLE LATER WAS WE WERE WAITING ON CHEMTREC TO TELL US ABOUT HOW DANGERS THIS CHEMICAL WAS.
